## Task 4 — Count Down with a while Loop

### Question 1. What is the role of the line `counter = counter - 1;`? What would happen without it?

The purpose of this line is to reduce the value of the `counter` variable by 1 during each iteration of the loop. It serves as the exit mechanism for the loop.

Without this statement, the value of `counter` would remain unchanged. Since the loop condition would continue to be true, the program would enter an infinite loop, repeatedly printing the same value and never reaching `"Liftoff!"` or any code after the loop.

### Question 2. Rewrite the countdown to start from 7 instead of 5.

```cpp
int count = 7;
```

This will make the countdown start from 7 instead of 5.

### Question 3. In your own words, what is the difference between `setup()` and a `while` loop? They both run code — what makes them different?

Although both execute code, they serve different purposes.

`setup()` is a special Arduino function that runs automatically once when the board powers on or resets. It is mainly used to initialize hardware and configure settings.

A `while` loop is a control structure that repeatedly executes a block of code as long as a specified condition remains true. It can be used inside `setup()` or `loop()` and may execute many times depending on the condition.

